# Since deleting 1005 ibu or 62 abv values could be detrimental to our analysis, I will impute the values using the mean or median this function checks for NA values, then replaces them with the mean of the ABV values without the NA's.
mean_Abv <-
  beers_breweries %>% 
  group_by(Style) %>% 
  summarise(mean_abv = mean(ABV, na.rm = TRUE)) %>% 
  mutate(mean_aBV = mean_abv)
  
# joining mean_abv to main df
beers_breweries = left_join(beers_breweries,mean_Abv, by = "Style")

beers_breweries$ABV <- ifelse(is.na(beers_breweries$ABV), beers_breweries$mean_abv, beers_breweries$ABV)

# this function checks for NA values, then replaces them with the mean of the IBU values without the NA's due to its potential skewed distribution
mean_IBU <-
  beers_breweries %>% 
  group_by(Style) %>% 
  summarise(mean_IBU = mean(IBU, na.rm = TRUE)) %>% 
  mutate(mean_ibu = mean_IBU)

# joining mean_IBU to main df
beers_breweries = left_join(beers_breweries,mean_IBU, by = "Style")

beers_breweries$IBU <- ifelse(is.na(beers_breweries$IBU), 
                              beers_breweries$mean_ibu, beers_breweries$IBU)

# sanity check 2
missing_counts <- sapply(beers_breweries, function(x) sum(is.na(x)))
print(missing_counts)
##      Beer_ID          ABV          IBU   Brewery_id        Style       Ounces 
##            0            0           52            0            0            0 
##         City        State    Beer_Name Brewery_Name     mean_abv     mean_aBV 
##            0            0            0            0            0            0 
##     mean_IBU     mean_ibu 
##           52           52
beers_breweries <-
  beers_breweries %>% 
    filter(!is.na(IBU))

To get rid of the NAs we use a measure of center (mean) and impute. In both instances we take the mean of the ABV and IBU for each style of beverage, then replace the NA value in the ABV column based on the Style of beverage it is. This takes care of the 62 NAs for ABV column. We do the same for the IBU column. Lastly, to address the NAs under Style we took the mode (another measure of center) and replaced the five NAs with the most popular Style.

Generally, an increase in ABV is associated with an increase in IBU. This makes sense because the more bitter beverages on average are IPAs that have a higher ABV as well. 8. Budweiser Would Also Like to Investigate the Difference w/ Respect to IBU and ABV Between IPAs (India Pale Ales) and Other Types of Ale (any beer with Ale in its name other than IPA) You Decide to Use kNN Classification to Investigate This Relationship. Provide statistical evidence one way or the other.

#Setting seed for reproducibility
set.seed(321)

# Filter dataset for IPAs and Ales
beers_breweries_knn <-
  beers_breweries %>% 
    mutate(Classification = as.factor(ifelse( grepl("India Pale Ale|IPA",Style, ignore.case = TRUE) == 1, "IPA",
                                              ifelse(grepl("Ale",Style, ignore.case = FALSE) == 1, "Other", "")))) %>% 
  filter(Classification != "") %>% 
  droplevels(beers_breweries$Classification)

dim(beers_breweries_knn) #1538 rows
## [1] 1538   16
# partitioning the data
trainInd = sample(seq(1,1538,1), 1538*.7) # creating random sample indexes
training = beers_breweries_knn[trainInd,] # train data
testing = beers_breweries_knn[-trainInd,] # test data

# using knn to classify style of beer using ABV and IBU in the new testing set
classifications = knn(training[,c(2,3)], testing[,c(2,3)], training$Classification, k = 15, prob = TRUE)
# creating confusion matrix to calculate the accuracy, misclassification rate,
# sensitivity and specificity
confusionMatrix(classifications, testing$Classification )
## Confusion Matrix and Statistics
##

## Prediction IPA Other

accuracy <- sum(classifications == testing$Classification) / length(testing$Classification)
paste("Accuracy:", round(accuracy * 100, 2), "%")
## [1] "Accuracy: 88.1 %"
  • Accuracy: Approximately 88.1% percent of the predictions were correct (both true positives and true negatives).
  • Sensitivity: About 77.59% of the actual IPAs were correctly identified. This means that out of all the IPAs, our model was able to identify 77.59% correctly.
  • Specificity: Approximately 94% of the time, our model correctly identified Other beers. This tells us that its quite good at identifying beers that are not IPAs.
# Using statistical tests to see if the differences in IBU and ABV between IPAs and other 
# Ales are statistically significant

# T-test for ABV
t_test_abv <- t.test(ABV ~ Classification, data = beers_breweries_knn)

# T-test for IBU
t_test_ibu <- t.test(IBU ~ Classification, data = beers_breweries_knn)

# Output the t-test results
list(ABV_T_Test = t_test_abv, IBU_T_Test = t_test_ibu)

ABV

The t-test results show that there is a statistically significant difference in ABV between IPAs and Pale Ales, with IPAs having a higher mean ABV (p-value 2.2e-16 from Welchs Two Sample t-test). The extremely low p-value suggests that the observed difference is very unlikely to be due to chance. This could indicate that IPAs are generally stronger in terms of alcohol content compared to Pale Ales. This insight can be valuable for Budweiser in tailoring their product offerings to meet consumer preferences or in targeting marketing efforts for different beer styles.

IBU

There is strong evidence to suggest a statistically significant difference in bitterness between IPAs and Pale Ales, with IPAs having a higher mean IBU (p-value 2.2e-16 from Welchs Two Sample t-test). This finding suggests that when it comes to bitterness, these two styles of beer cater to distinct taste preferences. For Budweiser, this might imply a focus on marketing IPAs to consumers who prefer a bitter taste and Pale Ales to those who prefer a less bitter beer.

9. Knock their socks off! Find one other useful inference from the data that you feel Budweiser may be able to find value in.

Given the data an interesting area of investigation could involve analyzing beer styles popularity and market trends, such as the relationship between ABV (Alcohol By Volume), IBU (International Bitterness Units), and the popularity or prevalence of beer styles. For this analysis, we can hypothesize that beers with specific ABV and IBU ranges tend to be more popular or prevalent, indicating consumer preference trends.

#Exploring the distribution of ABV and IBU across different beer styles


# ABV distribution across top 10 beer styles
# Filter for only the top 10 most common beer styles
top_styles <- beers_breweries %>%
  count(Style) %>%
  top_n(10, n) %>%
  pull(Style)

filtered_data <- beers_breweries %>%
  filter(Style %in% top_styles)
library(ggplot2)
# Creating the boxplot with the filtered data
ggplot(filtered_data, aes(x = reorder(Style, ABV, FUN = median), y = ABV)) + 
  geom_boxplot(aes(color = Style)) + 
  theme(axis.text.x = element_text(angle = 45, hjust = 1),
        legend.position = "none") +
  labs(title = "ABV Distribution Across Top 10 Beer Styles", x = "Beer Style", y = "ABV") +
  theme(plot.title = element_text(hjust = 0.5))  # Center the plot title

A quick glance at the plot suggests that there is considerable diversity in ABV across beer styles. Some styles, like American Double/Imperial IPA, have a higher median ABV, reflecting their characteristically stronger profiles. The range of ABV values within styles could reflect diverse consumer preferences, with some consumers preferring lighter beers and others seeking stronger options.

# IBU distribution across beer styles
ggplot(filtered_data, aes(x = reorder(Style, IBU, FUN = median), y = IBU)) + 
  geom_boxplot(aes(color = Style)) + 
  theme(axis.text.x = element_text(angle = 45, hjust = 1)) +
  theme(plot.title = element_text(hjust = 0.5),
        legend.position = "none") + 
  labs(title = "IBU Distribution Across Top 10 Beer Styles", x = "Beer Style", y = "IBU")

Beer styles with higher IBU are often perceived as more bitter, and this plot shows which styles tend to have higher bitterness levels. This information could help Budweiser decide on product development strategies, such as creating beers that fit popular or niche bitterness profiles. Understanding the range and common values of IBU for popular styles can also inform quality control and consistency efforts in beer production.
